Clint Webb  

  • its very simple, if you let me explain

  • so, lets say the first server starts off with 16 buckets.

  • thats a mask of 0xf. or 0x000F if you prefer

  • 16 buckets.

  • so if a client connects at that point... its gets a hashmask list with 16 entries.

  • Each entry would be pointing to that one server.

  • So another server joins the cluster.

  • It is wildly out of balance with the other server. First server has 100% of the load, #2 has 0%.

  • So #1 gives #2 one of its buckets.

  • It starts transferring data from... say... bucket 16 to #2.

  • While the sync is going on, the clients still think #1 is responsible for bucket 16, which it is.

    •
09:38:36 PM
Brian Gorrie  

  • yep hats how you explained i theother day

09:38:54 PM
Clint Webb  

  • yeah, hold on.

  • When #2 is in sync. It becomes the master for bucket 16, and #1 becomes the backup. Both of them send an update to their connected clients.

  • So thats transferring of buckets.

  • But lets say you have 16 nodes.... or one bucket is somehow heavier than the others.

  • The bucket needs to be split.

  • ... so... lets say bucket 16 needs to be split.

  • and it is on server #2.

  • 16 is actually 0xF.

  • Whcih fits inside the existing MASK that server #2 is using.

  • but it cant split with the same mask, so it must add a digit to the mask.

  • so its mask shifts, and goes from 0x000F to 0x00FF.

  • And bucket number 16 (i chose a poor number for an example)

  • gets split into 16 smaller buckets.

  • 000F becomes 000F, 001F, 002F, 003F, 004F... and so on up to 00FF.

  • note that all those 16 new buckets still fit into the old mask of 0x000F/000F. So it hasn't changed anything for the clients yet.

  • two ways

09:55:22 PM
Clint Webb  

  • my concept was to start off with big buckets, and make them smaller and smaller till the cluster settles.

  • it doesn't have to be managed, and is rather organic.

  • oh, now here is another genius part.

  • you ready?

  • so, the nodes communicate with each, and ping/pong back and forth.

  • normally when a client connects to a server trying to do something to a bucket, that the server is only a backup for... the server says "sorry, talk to the primary server which is.... "

  • but if the ping/pong fails... it goes into a special mode.

  • it doesn't do anything yet.

  • but a mode is set.

  • but the next time a client connects to it, and says "do this please"... because the client couldn't connect to the primary and instead sent it to a backup, the server decides that it must now be the primary for that bucket. It will instantly become the primary.

  • So the ordering of the 'backups' of a bucket becomes important if we decide to have more than one.

  • The first backup will be the one that previously held that bucket, and it will be the one that has the most recent data for it. SO it is logical that it become the primary

  • When the failed server comes online again, it will be informed that it was dropped, and it will need to sync up again, and will become a backup for those buckets (at the end of the backup list)

  • cool huh?

  • Avoiding a master controller yet again.

  • with little impact to clients.

  • the servers dont push promotion, the clients do.

  • might have to take a little bit of care to avoid it thrashing back and forth.

  • what do you think?

Clint Webb  

  • right right. Its simple, I'll show you.

  • I thought I told you this before

  • but anyway.

  • ClusteredLong blah = cluster.newLong('something');
    blah.set(129323);

  • the client code, would convert the name 'something' into a hash.

  • like: f96e47e0a88f32808f44f837719995de

  • it sends to the server the hash and the data

  • the data being a long, but the server doesnt really care what the data is.

  • but the server notes, that the item is just that, a single item.

  • but then you have a map.

  • ClusteredMap blah = cluster.newMap("mappy");

  • the client code would do a hash on "mappy".

  • this becomes the hash for the entire map. But doesn't actually represent individual items.

  • so then you add an entry to the map.

  • blah.set("whatever", 12345);

  • you could do a map with <string, int> or <int, string> or whatever. its up to the client to figure all that out.

  • so now, you have the HASH for the entire map.

  • and you generate a hash for "whatever"

  • but the "whatever" hash needs to be salted so that it doesn't conflict with a single item called "whatever".

  • we can figure out what kind of salt would work best.

  • but this time when that map item is sent over the wire, it include the HASH of the MAP, and the HASH of the item in the map "whatever" in this case.

  • it sends it to the server responsible for the bucket that "whatever" mapts to. The key or index item in the map.

  • the server does its thing, and it informs the server responsible for the MAP that it has added another item to the map (to keep a count)

  • so map items, and regular items are treated slightly differently, BUT on the server side, each item of the map ends up in distributed buckets just like other items.

  • so on the server, items in the btree also have the map hash if appropriate.

  • And it would need to keep a seperate list... unsorted really... of all the entries in the bucket that belong to that map. So that when the client says "give me all the entries for that map" it can.

  • so you see it doesn't need a special index for the map though.... cause where would that go?

  • it just creates a slightly different hash, but then does pretty much the same thing as a single item.

  • does that work?
